John Edward: Essential Language Skills for Global Citizens
Private schools in Scotland hold the record for academic excellence and this has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent results in exams, further reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other fields.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further education at the highest levels, for their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailored educational curriculum, we are witnessing how the branch of modern languages continues to be a widespread and preferred choice throughout schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to someone in a language that they understand, your words are heard.
If you speak to him in your own language, your words are in his heart.”
These words are a powerful reminder that we can't rely only on English when we want to build relationships with people from foreign countries.
From the results of last year's exams, we can find that languages are leading the lists of results, with the highest rate of passing grades among private schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied foreign languages have received a maximum A score.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students had received the maximum A score in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied for German, 69 percent of those who studied for French and 63 percent of those who studied for Spanish also received A score.
This shows that private schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as one of the vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, the branch of foreign languages is considered as important as the branches of STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of private schools and beyond.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills found that among the main difficulties employers faced in filling vacancies, 17% of them were related to lack of language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With the addition of jobs that require the proficiency of foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have real advantages in the future, as a master of such a long-term ability.
The ability to communicate directly with strangers will automatically position a multilingual person over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey, which included over 4,000 adults from the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to develop a conversation, and French was the only one-hundredth of people to speak a foreign language.
That's why investing in language learning is important for today's children.
The proficiency of many languages, especially the proficiency of the languages of developing countries, will give children a better chance of employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different in terms of the languages taught in them.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will offer languages that are considered the most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a range of languages from which you can choose in private schools, with pedagogical staff consisting of specialists in the field.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a school environment that will prepare children and "weaponize" them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future.
In these times, it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as truly a "skill of international communication."
Private schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
