Harvard Students Take Lessons on How to Get Enough Rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has involved all students to sleep more, in an effort to fight the growing culture of study 'masks' through the use of caffeine by these 'painless'.
One academic noted that students at the number one university in the world often don't know when it comes to the most basic things about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the lecture course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start this course after giving a briefing on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why is this being told to me now, in my last year?'
She said no one had ever talked to her about the importance of sleep before — something that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, included in the program for the first time this year, explains to students the essential elements of how habits of good sleep help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of the university's medical services, said the university decided to introduce this course after finding that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The course, which lasts one hour, involves a series of interactive tasks.
On one side is a view of a guest room, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, athletes and books in order to be explained the effects of caffeine and lighting and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of the routine of riding the clock.
In another part, participants are explained how sleep deprivation over a long period of time increases the risk of heart attack, ischemia, depression and cancer.
A map of the camp, with interactive icons, further encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that students' behaviors will not change immediately.
But we believe that they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know, the health impact when choosing to smoke," said Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride to spend “a sleepless night” continues to exist, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring you get enough sleep, of good quality, should be the students' "secret weapon" to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation takes the brain into a hunger mode, making them feel hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course after attending one of his lessons last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to turn it into a course for the whole camp.
He hopes that the next step, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining competing institutions.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students should set a clock with bells on when to go to bed, and also on when to wake up, and be aware of the damaging effects of the ‘blue light’ coming out of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can bring out the biological rhythm of the work.
