The creator of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the founder of the World Wide Web, is creating a company that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company built from Berners-Lee’s open-source platform, called Solid.
'Solid' allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people are allowed to access a certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal behind Inrupt is “world domination.”
"We have to do it now," he said of this innovative company.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid's technology to allow people to create "storage of their personal data on the network" or a POD.
It can contain contact lists, lists of things to do, music lists, and other personal and professional tools.
It's the same as having available in a browser and at the same time Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify.
What is unique about storing personal data on the network is the fact that it is entirely up to the user what kind of information they will access.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to bring together the right resources, processes, and skills to help Solid be available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several contracted developers to work on this project, and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, tech developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google whether or not they should introduce a total change where all of their business models are completely reversed overnight.
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a post on the Medium published Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's mission "is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the newly built Solid network."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Over the past few months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the network's independence debate.
While founding Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Network Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm very optimistic about this new era of networking," Berners-Lee added.
