Below are some facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the central province of Sulawesi, located at the bottom of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Sulawesi, with a population of about 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when it was hit by an earthquake and tsunami.
Donggala is a regency stretching over 300 km (180 miles) of coastline to the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The Regency, a smaller administrative region than the province, had an estimated population of about 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming are the province's main economic activities, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel extraction is also important in the province, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the other side of the Sulawesi coast.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency, Palu and Donggala have been hit several times by a tsunami over the past 100 years.
In 1938, a tsunami claimed the lives of more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, another tsunami struck the western part of Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the seismic zone of the Ring of Fire in the Pacific Ocean and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Below are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On December 26, a powerful earthquake on the western coast of Aceh province in Indonesia, in the northern part of Sumatra, caused a tsunami that struck 14 states, causing 226,000 deaths along the Indian Ocean coastline, more than half of which are in the Indian Ocean.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds have lost their lives on Nias Island, on the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude quake hit the south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, causing a tsunami that crashed on the south coast and killed about 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude quake struck near the city of Padang, the capital of western Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude quake hit one of the islands of Mentawai, in Sumatra, causing a tsunami up to 10 meters high that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh, bringing destruction and panic to people after recalling the devastation caused by the 2004 deadly earthquake and tsunami.
This time, there was no tsunami, but more than 100 people lost their lives to the collapse of buildings.
2018: Heavy earthquakes hit the tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, most of them in the northern part of the island.
